The David A. Straz Jr. Center for the Performing Arts has announced its 2022-23 Broadway season, and it’s packed with favorites both classic and contemporary. Standouts in the eight-show Broadway series include Tina — The Tina Turner Musical, Jagged Little Pill (featuring the music of Alanis Morissette), Chicago and To Kill a Mockingbird. Special return engagements include Hamilton, which is slated for Dec. 28-Jan. 22, and Wicked, which runs March 8-26, 2023. “Touring Broadway is back in Tampa in a big, big way,” Straz Center president and CEO Judy Lisi said in a news release. “We’ve got an astonishing season planned that includes audience favorites, award winners, R&B, rock ‘n’ roll and a couple of shows that were originally announced for the 2020-2021 slate and postponed due to the pandemic.” Six (Nov. 1-6, 2022): In this musical written by Toby Marlow and Lucy Moss, the six wives of Henry VIII “take the mic to remix 500 years of historical heartbreak into an exuberant celebration of 21st century girl power.” It was a Critic’s Pick from The New York Times and hailed as “inspirational” by The Washington Post. Hadestown (Nov. 29-Dec. 4, 2022): Winner of eight Tony Awards, including Best Musical, and the 2020 Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album, this love story intertwines the mythical tales of Orpheus and Eurydice and King Hades and his wife Persephone. Tina — The Tina Turner Musical (Jan. 31-Feb. 5, 2023): The musical reveals the comeback story of the legendary Queen of Rock ‘n’ Roll. It features popular songs from her catalogue and was written by Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright Katori Hall. Chicago (Feb. 21-26, 2023): After more than 25 years, Chicago is still a Broadway favorite. Set in the Jazz Age, it features some of the most iconic songs and dance moves on Broadway. With six Tony Awards, two Olivier Awards and a Grammy Award, it really is all that jazz. Harper Lee’s To Kill a Mockingbird (April 11-16, 2023): Academy Award winner Aaron Sorkin’s adaptation of Harper Lee’s Pulitzer Prize-winning book has been widely acclaimed. Emmy Award-winning actor Richard Thomas will play the role of Atticus Finch in the national tour. Ain’t Too Proud (May 2-7, 2023): Subtitled “The Life and Times of the Temptations,” this musical follows the story of the R&B supergroup during a decade of civil unrest. It’s been nominated for 12 Tony Awards and won the Tony for Best Choreography. Expect to hear favorite songs including My Girl, Just My Imagination and Papa Was a Rolling Stone. Jagged Little Pill (May 16-21, 2023): The musical based on Alanis Morissette’s music boasts a Tony Award-winning book by Diablo Cody and follows a “perfectly imperfect American family.” The season also features a show in the intimate Jaeb Theater. Shear Madness (Feb. 15-April 8, 2023): This comedy whodunit is set in the Shear Madness hairstyling salon. During the course of the action, a murder is committed, and the audience gets to spot the clues, question the suspects and solve the mystery. In addition to the eight-show Broadway series, The Straz will present two special return engagements. Hamilton (Dec. 28, 2022-Jan. 22, 2023): Lin-Manuel Miranda’s smash hit tells the story of American founding father Alexander Hamilton through a score that blends hip-hop, jazz, R&B and Broadway. It has won Tony, Grammy and Olivier awards, the Pulitzer Prize for Drama and an unprecedented special citation from the Kennedy Center Honors. Wicked (March 8-26, 2023): Set in the Land of Oz long before Dorothy arrives, the musical tells the story of the realm’s two witches and their unlikely friendship. Current Bank of America Broadway at The Straz season ticket holders will receive renewal invoices the week of March 7 and must renew by April 26 to guarantee their seats. Patrons can sign up now to become new season ticket holders. Prices for the eight-show season package range from $258.50 to $793.20. For more information, call the Straz Center Ticket Sales Office at 813-229-7827 or visit strazcenter.org. Individual show tickets will go on sale at a later date, to be announced. David A. Straz Jr. Center for the Performing Arts, 1010 N Macinnes Place, Tampa.